# Premise/Description {#premise/description}

Our game is a 3D physics-based puzzle platformer and social narrative game, where the player will progress through 4 chambers in order to discover themself and escape the island. Throughout the game, the player will navigate evolving rooms, finding hidden keys and mastering helpful abilities to traverse the space. At the end of their journey, their choices and personal statistics will culminate in a unique cosmetic look and playstyle assignment.

The game is inspired by games like Portal and The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild (and by extension, other Zelda games), where both games focus on puzzle-solving through the use of an assortment of items and physics-based methods. In addition, the puzzles will be encapsulated through dungeons (consisting of various rooms and decor), each their own theme and puzzle design. The game itself is about a lost soul awakening in a realm called The Verge, where it must journey across four floating islands, each with puzzles that help the player grasp their true Passions, Principles, Partners and Plans. By solving these puzzles and experimenting with different abilities, the soul uncovers what kind of problem solver it truly is before returning to Earth, without a memory of the journey.

Adding onto the focus of puzzle-solving, our game encourages planning ahead and critical thinking. The game provides many playstyles in the form of our job system (name pending), where players are able to acquire roles that provide a unique ability at the cost of some weakness. These jobs can help greatly with the puzzle-solving process, but the catch is that not every job can solve any problem (i.e. only certain ones can solve a certain problem with the others cannot). This dynamic of pros and cons with each job, as well as the option of using less effective items (which provide a weaker, but still useful ability), encourages a lot of experimentation and planning, which is the main goal for our game.

By the end of the game, players will come out with a better understanding of themselves. They’ll learn what kind of playstyles, values, habits, and archetypes they enjoy practicing just by playing and experimenting with the game’s mechanics. To help with this, the game actually keeps track of certain statistics, tracking their progress and what decisions they’ve made. These statistics are then used to provide a label to the player, providing a good description of what kind of player they are and what their personality is like. Self-discovery is our major goal/theme, and our puzzle-platformer encourages players to relax and take their time to figure things out.

* Puzzle-Platformer  
* 3D, Third-Person  
* Social Narrative (focus of Self-Discovery)

# Interesting and Meaningful Choices {#interesting-and-meaningful-choices}

* Tessamark:  
  * Track everything the player does, in terms of minor choices and major choices  
  * Is the means of displaying game information (i.e. map, stats, objective, etc.)  
* Each dungeon consists of multiple puzzles relating to a certain theme (based on the Four P’s)  
* Each puzzle can contain multiple solutions based on the player’s job, but only certain jobs can actually solve the puzzle  
* Encourage players to experiment and plan out a solution. “No need to rush/Take Your Time”

# Mechanics {#mechanics}

* Player will start with a base character with no special traits  
* Early on, they obtain items that grant them small abilities, making puzzles a bit easier.  
* As the player progresses, they can unlock remnants (special outfits) that when combined with the right item, they can unlock a job  
* Each job will provide a special ability/trait/passive, but at the cost of some weakness/drawback (see Character Design)  
* Different remnants \+ Items \= Different jobs   
* For example: Helmet \+ Hammer \= Builder  
* Stat Tracker in the form of the Tessamark

Unresolved Design Choices:

* Distribution method of outfits and handhelds (i.e. collectables found through the level, unlocked through some currency/EXP, maybe everything is unlocked at the start like in Zelda: A Link Between Worlds)  
* Allow Player to switch between unlocked jobs freely or limit their usage  
* How many items can be held at a time? (i.e. limited inventory space)

# Narrative {#narrative}

* Lost Soul finding themself in order to return to their world –  
* A person from Earth’s soul is brought to another dimension called “the Verge.” This dimension is one where a person’s soul goes to find themselves and navigate through 4 floating islands of self discovery before being brought back to Earth. Once a soul goes back to Earth, the person who they go back into will not remember anything from when their soul was in that realm.   
* In the Verge, souls traverse through four floating islands, solving puzzles to discover things about themselves. There is an island where the soul will discover   
* Player character can be molded to fit the real personality of the player  
* Narrator: Stanley Parable-type guide, reacting to certain choices the player makes

Final Narrative for now: 

The player is a lost soul who has just entered a different dimension called “The Verge.” The Verge is a realm where souls explore four islands of self discovery before returning to Earth. Each island represents a core category that will drive you towards self exploration. The first island that you will explore and solve puzzles in is that of Passions, then of Principles, Partners, and Plans. As the player completes puzzles in each one and experiments with whatever abilities they like most that come with each island, they will discover what type of problem solver they are. 

The Narrator serves as a guide who will introduce players to certain puzzles but not provide solutions. 

When the soul completes all four islands, the Tessamark will appear with all the stats evaluated from your journey along with what type of player you are. The souls of The Verge will return to Earth fundamentally changed after this, but without any conscious memory of The Verge.

# Inputs and Controls {#inputs-and-controls}

* Controller and KBM support (with rebind support)  
* One special ability per Job  
* Tessamark display for pause menu  
* Interact button for Interactables like levers, doors, picking up items, etc.  
* 3D ground movement  
* Jump

# Character Design {#character-design}

* Simple, malleable  
* Customization of look and cosmetic items to fit the player  
  * Small or no influence on playability based on what the player has chosen  
  * Mario Odyssey Style: split outfit into a few key pieces that can be swapped and combined  
    * Hat  
      * Clothing  
      * Handprop?  
  * Jobs (name pending):  
    * **Builder:**   
      * \+ can create support structures (basically Fortnite)  
      * \- is limited by a resource meter (like Steve’s resource meter in Super Smash Bros Ultimate)![][image1]  
    * **Musician**:  
      * \+ uses sound waves or instruments to move objects at a distance or propel themself  
      * \- requires precise aim and timing of sound waves  
    * **Athlete**:  
      * \+ provides superhuman-like strength and movement abilities  
      * \- usage of abilities limited by a stamina meter  
    * **Artist**:  
      * can draw certain elements (like scribblenauts?)  
    * Other jobs: Baker/Chef, A firefighter/police officer archetype, Scientist/ Programmer, Doctor
